data.content:
Here are the three breaking changes and fixes:

### 1. `Buffer.cs` — `[InlineArray]` on `record struct`

C# 13 disallows `[InlineArray]` on `record struct` because the synthesized `Equals`/`GetHashCode` only inspected the first element, silently producing wrong behavior. **Fix:** use a plain `struct`:

```csharp
[System.Runtime.CompilerServices.InlineArray(10)]
struct Buffer
{
    private int _element0;
}
```

### 2. `Generator.cs` — `stackalloc` in local function inside iterator

C# 13 partially lifts the ban on `unsafe` code in iterators (to support `ref struct`). A side effect is that local functions inside iterators are now subject to iterator safety rules, so `stackalloc` in a local function within an iterator is an error. **Fix:** extract the local function to a standalone `static` method:

```csharp
unsafe class DataGenerator
{
    IEnumerable<int> Generate()
    {
        yield return 1;
        Process();
    }

    static void Process()
    {
        int* p = stackalloc int[10];
        // ... work with pointer
    }
}
```

### 3. `Resolver.cs` — collection expression overload ambiguity

C# 13 adds a new overload-resolution preference: `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is better than `Span<T>` for collection expressions. In C# 12 the call `Process([])` resolved to `Span<object>` (since `object` subsumes `int`). In C# 13 the new span-kind preference (`ReadOnlySpan` > `Span`) conflicts with the element-type preference, making the call **ambiguous**. **Fix:** disambiguate with an explicit target type:

```csharp
static void Main()
{
    Process((ReadOnlySpan<int>)[]);
}
```
